The 5 Documents (Corpus)
Doc 1: "The cat sat on the mat."

Doc 2: "The dog chased the cat."

Doc 3: "The bird flew over the mat."

Doc 4: "A dog barked at the bird."

Doc 5: "The cat and dog are friends."

from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import TfidfVectorizer
import pandas as pd

corpus = [
    "The cat sat on the mat.",
    "The dog chased the cat.",
    "The bird flew over the mat.",
    "A dog barked at the bird.",
    "The cat and dog are friends."
]

# Initialize and fit the vectorizer
vectorizer = TfidfVectorizer(stop_words='english')
tfidf_matrix = vectorizer.fit_transform(corpus)

# Get feature names (the words)
feature_names = vectorizer.get_feature_names_out()

# Create a readable table for the first document
df = pd.DataFrame(tfidf_matrix.toarray(), columns=feature_names)
print("Top Keywords for Document 1:")
print(df.iloc[0].sort_values(ascending=False).head(3))

Top Keywords & Explanation
For Document 1 ("The cat sat on the mat"), the top keywords would likely be:

Sat: High TF-IDF because it only appears in this document (Unique).

Mat: Moderate TF-IDF because it appears in Doc 1 and Doc 3 (Slightly less unique).

Cat: Lower TF-IDF compared to "Sat" because it appears in 3 out of 5 documents (Common).

Why this matters: If a user searches for "Sat," this document is the perfect match. If they search for "The," every document matches, so "The" has a TF-IDF score of 0.
